<body>
  <header>
    <h1>Difference between IaaS, PaaS, and SaaS</h1>
  </header>

  <table>
    <tr>
      <th>Aspect</th>
      <th>IaaS</th>
      <th>PaaS</th>
      <th>SaaS</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Definition</td>
      <td>Infrastructure as a Service – provides virtual servers, storage, networking.</td>
      <td>Platform as a Service – provides tools/frameworks for building & deploying apps.</td>
      <td>Software as a Service – delivers ready-to-use software over the internet.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Example</td>
      <td>AWS EC2, Google Compute Engine, Microsoft Azure VM</td>
      <td>Google App Engine, Heroku, Vercel</td>
      <td>Gmail, Dropbox, Google Docs</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>User Control</td>
      <td>High – you manage OS, apps, and runtime.</td>
      <td>Medium – you manage only apps and data.</td>
      <td>Low – everything managed by provider.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Best For</td>
      <td>Developers needing max control over infra.</td>
      <td>Developers focusing on coding not infra.</td>
      <td>End-users who just need software.</td>
    </tr>
  </table>

  <footer>
    <p>Created for Cloud Computing Lab Experiment</p>
  </footer>
